{
  "text": "We are also aware of different applications of normalized mutual information in literature. The first one is used for data clustering [CITATION_1] , in which the normalized mutual information of two attributes x and y is defined as 2\u00b7I (x;y) max A\u2208{1,...,k} (H (A))+max B\u2208{1,...,g} (H (B)) , where A represents possible cluster labels and B represents possible category labels. Normalized mutual information is also found in the area of image processing [CITATION_2] , where it is defined as",
